    "topic": "Cities on River Banks in India - Overview",
    "subtopics": [
      {
        "subtopic": "Overview",
        "content": "India’s geography and culture have been deeply influenced by its rivers, which have supported ancient civilizations, trade, and urban growth. From the sacred Ganga and Yamuna in the north to the mighty Godavari, Krishna, and Cauvery in the south, rivers play a key role in shaping cities and ecosystems.\n\nRiverbank cities like Ahmedabad (Sabarmati) and Varanasi (Ganga) are important industrial and religious centers. Recently, Patna (Ganga) has gained importance due to inland waterway projects, while Hyderabad (Musi) focuses on river restoration. Ayodhya (Sarayu) is emerging as a cultural hub with the Ram Temple development boosting tourism.\n\nKey Points:\n• Rivers like the Ganga, Yamuna, Godavari, Krishna, and Cauvery shape India’s geography and cities.\n• Cities on rivers combine history, religion, economy, and environment.\n• Ahmedabad (Sabarmati) – Industrial city; Varanasi (Ganga) – religious center.\n• Patna (Ganga) – important for inland waterways.\n• Hyderabad (Musi) – river cleaning projects are ongoing.\n• Ayodhya (Sarayu) – cultural growth due to the Ram Temple.\n• Projects like Namami Gange and Smart Cities focus on rivers.\n\nThis article offers a state-wise overview of major Indian cities on rivers, useful for aspirants of bank, SSC, and UPSC exams."
